<TR>
<!-- <TD></TD> -->
<TD VALIGN="top">"Everyday you think, well maybe we should stop. Maybe there's no point to this, because all the sounds you made, that made you so happy, have been sucked of everything they meant. It's a total headf***." Thus mused Thom Yorke recently on the cruel nature of alt-pop megastardom and the grave consequences of other people ever hearing your songs. And thus comes Kid A. The party begins with the poetically plangent Everything In Its Right Place, where Thom hangs himself off the meaningful mantra "yesterday I woke up sucking a lemon..." (the message of such (literally) acid observation being: 'deconstruct <I>that</I> you pesky pseudy students!'), before hitting us with experimentally aimless Aphex Twin outtake Kid A. There's something more akin to the expected angst-pop in The National Anthem, but it's still not quite Karma Police. And it has a saxophone. Then How To Disappear Completely depressingly recalls bits of Embrace, there's more wibbling (Trefingers), a couple of songs sort of (Optimistic, In Limbo), a wibbly song (Idioteque), a whiney song (Morning Bell) and - at last - The Anthem (Motion Picture Soundtrack). And that's it. Ten songs. Fifty minutes. Done. On first listen. Radiohead, being clever devils and tortured artists will not make it easy for the humble fan either: they demand dedication. These songs are worth it. There are mumbled wisdoms to decipher, buried sounds to detect and, God help us all, <I>grooves</I> to get into. This is a band consistently doing differently interesting things. Being indulgent is definitely okay if you've got a talent and a vision to indulge. And Radiohead have several.<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="-2" COLOR="#666666"><I>By Esther Sadler</I></FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
